    <%- include("../partials/head", { title, pageType }) %>

<body>
    <%- include("../partials/pageHeader", { heading, date }) %>

    <main class="container day-content">
        <%- include("../partials/toc") %>

        <div class="doc-content">
            <section class="doc-section">
                <h2>Overview</h2>
                <p>
                    Day 6 was about client vs server, environment variables, and improving how we structure our frontend.
                </p>
                <p>
                    We also worked with npm scripts, semantic HTML, and styling things like making the footer stay at the bottom.
                </p>
            </section>

            <section class="doc-section">
                <h2>NPM Scripts</h2>
                <p>
                    We used <code>package.json</code> to define scripts so we don't have to type long commands every time we want to run the app.
                </p>

                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-json">
"scripts": {
    "start-dev": "cross-env PORT=8080 NODE_ENV=DEV node app.js",
    "start-prod": "cross-env PORT=80 node app.js"
}
                </code></pre>
                
                <p>Instead of writing everything manually in the terminal, we can now just run:</p>

                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-bash">
npm run start-dev
                </code></pre>
                
                <p>This makes things more consistent, especially when working in groups. Everyone runs the app the same way.</p>
            </section>

            <section class="doc-section">
                <h2>Environment Variables</h2>
                <p>Environment variables are values that are not written directly in the code, but instead set outside the application.</p>

                <p>We used them for things like setting the port:</p>

    <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-js">
const PORT = process.env.PORT || 8080;

const server = app.listen(PORT, () => {
    console.log("Server started on port", server.address().port);
});
                </code></pre>

                <p>If no environment variable is set, it just falls back to 8080.</p>

                <h3>Why this is useful</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Different setup for development and production</li>
                    <li>Avoid hardcoding values in the code</li>
                    <li>Safer for things like API keys or passwords</li>
                </ul>

                <h3>Short-circuit Syntax</h3>
                <p>In the example above, we use <code>||</code>, which is also called 'short-curcuit syntax'.</p>
                <p>It takes the first value (if it exists) and if not, then use the second one.</p>

                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-js">
const PORT = process.env.PORT || 8080;
                </code></pre>

                <p>So if <code>process.env.PORT</code> is defined, it will use that. But if not, it falls back to <code>8080</code>.</p>
                <p>This is very useful when you want a default value without writing an if-statement.</p>

                <p>Same idea works for other values, not just ports:</p>
                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-js">
const username = input || "guest";
                </code></pre>
            </section>

            <section class="doc-section">
                <h2>Semantic HTML</h2>
                <p>We started using semantic HTML like <code>nav</code>, <code>main</code> and <code>footer</code>.</p>

                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-html">
&lt;nav&gt;&lt;/nav&gt;
&lt;main&gt;&lt;/main&gt;
&lt;footer&gt;&lt;/footer&gt;
                </code></pre>

                <p>These tags describe what the content actually is, not just how it looks.</p>
                <p>It also helps with accessibility and makes the structure easier to read.</p>
            </section>

            <section class="doc-section">
                <h2>Project Structure</h2>
                <p>
                    We improved the project structure by separating pages and assets.
                </p>

                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-bash">
public/
├── assets/
│   ├── css/
│   ├── js/
│   └── images/
└── pages/
    ├── about/
    └── frontend/
                </code></pre>
                <p>This makes it easier to find things instead of everything being mixed together.</p>
                <p>Makes more sense when the project starts growing.</p>
            </section>

            <section class="doc-section">
                <h2>Sticky Footer</h2>
                <p>The problem was that the footer would float in the middle if there wasn't much content.</p>
                
                <p>We fixed it using flexbox:</p>

                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-css">
body {
    min-height: 95vh;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
}

main {
    flex: 1;
}
                </code></pre>
                <p>Result:</p>
                <p>With this simple setup, the footer sticks to the bottom of the page, no matter how much content is above it, which gives it a proffesional look.</p>
            </section>

            <section class="doc-section">
                <h2>CDN vs Local</h2>
                <p>We used a CDN to include styling to our code with <code>water.css</code> instead of writing all CSS ourselves.</p>

                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-html">
&lt;link rel="stylesheet" href="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/water.css@2/out/water.css"&gt;
                </code></pre>

                <h3>What is a CDN?</h3>
                <p>A CDN (Content Delivery Network) is basically a way to load files from the internet instead of storing them in your project.</p>
                <p>So instead of downloading a CSS file and putting it in your project, you just link it from somewhere else.</p>
                <p>And in this case, we are loading <code>water.css</code> directly from a CDN.</p>


                <h3>Why use it?</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Very quick to set up</li>
                    <li>Can include your own styling on top of the CDN</li>
                    <li>No need to install or manage files locally</li>
                    <li>Good for testing</li>
                </ul>

                <h3>Downsides</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>You are depending on a external service</li>
                    <li>If the CDN is down, your styling wont work</li>
                </ul>
            </section>

            <section class="doc-section">
                <h2>Reflections (Day 6)</h2>
                <ul>
                    <li>NPM scripts make running the app much easier, and more consistent</li>
                    <li>Improving the folder structure makes it easier to navigate the project</li>
                    <li>Semantic HTML feels simple but improves the styling structure</li>
                </ul>
            </section>
        </div>
    </main>

    <%- include("../partials/footer") %>